<p>In the latest development, President Trump said he would “100%” follow through on new tariffs targeting several European NATO allies unless they accept a deal for the US to acquire Greenland, escalating a dispute with Denmark and the European Union ahead of the World Economic Forum in Davos. European leaders have rejected any change to Greenland’s status and say they will protect their interests, while trying to avoid a lasting break with Washington. Denmark has also moved to reinforce its presence on the island as tensions rise, underscoring how the Arctic’s strategic importance is spilling into trade and alliance politics.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/P0fUrgplkKK22M5VyqPd3krwO8D3BY-jbKQ0O5BHjSQd0tO3SLdnUt7D5xb4jLotJDqIYkm3gyG5E4suK5T3_IKTDjO8vvZo6tNhchVIeJAK' alt='US President Donald Trump and French President Emmanuel Macron shake hands at a summit in Sharm el-Sheikh, Egypt (Oct. 13, 2025).' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Davos meeting: President Trump said he had a “very good” call with NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte and plans a Greenland-focused meeting at Davos.</li><li>Paris outreach: Trump posted screenshots of what he said were private messages from French President Emmanuel Macron, in which Macron questioned US aims on Greenland and offered to host a G7-format meeting in Paris on Thursday, plus a dinner invitation.</li><li>EU toolkit: EU officials discussed reviving previously suspended tariffs worth nearly $110 billion and other countermeasures, while describing a “carrot-and-stick” approach intended to deter escalation.</li><li>NATO surveillance: Denmark proposed that NATO begin surveillance operations around Greenland, with Danish officials framing it as strengthening Arctic security alongside Greenlandic participation.</li><li>Public pushback: Protests in Denmark have featured parody red caps reading “Make America Go Away,” with some sales tied to charitable fundraising, reflecting grassroots opposition to the takeover rhetoric.</li></ul><blockquote>We have &quot;no interest to pick a fight, but we will hold our ground&quot;. - Kaja Kallas</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Trump administration: President Trump argues US control of Greenland is necessary for national (and global) security and has linked that goal to tariff pressure on allied countries. (<a href='https://www.ft.com/content/500d9508-72a2-4b04-a225-33adbbf8af78'>Financial Times</a>)</li><li>European Union: EU leaders say they do not want a fight but will defend EU interests if tariff threats continue, while coordinating a joint approach. (<a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c4g5345ylk0o'>BBC News</a>)</li><li>Denmark: Copenhagen rejects being pressured into transferring Greenland and is proposing NATO surveillance and reinforcing deployments as it seeks to keep the issue within alliance security frameworks. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/1/20/denmark-sends-more-troops-to-greenland-amid-tensions-with-trump'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li><li>US Treasury: Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent urged Europe not to retaliate on tariffs, calling retaliation “very unwise” and encouraging countries to “let things play out”. (<a href='https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/watch-bessent-says-it-would-be-very-unwise-for-europe-to-retaliate-over-trump-threats-on-greenland'>PBS NewsHour</a>)</li><li>France: Macron signaled confusion over US objectives on Greenland and floated a Paris meeting format that could include Denmark, Ukraine, Syria and Russia, according to messages Trump shared and a Macron-linked source described as authentic. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1968037/trump-shares-messages-from-frances-macron-offering-g7-meeting-after-davos'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Russia (official reactions): Russian officials and aligned voices have publicly welcomed the US-Europe rift while also noting the Arctic’s security stakes, according to reporting on Moscow’s response. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/news/world/russia-central-asia/ar